    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay i get that part but what makes it different from just regular correlation? like if i have two gloves and i send one to the moon and keep one here, if i see mine is left handed i know the other is right handed. isnt that basically the same thing?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The key difference lies in *when* the property is decided. With your gloves, the handedness was fixed the moment they were packed; it was a predetermined reality. In quantum entanglement, the particles don't have a definite state (like \"left\" or \"right\") until the very moment one is measured. The act of measuring one particle *forces* both particles to instantly assume their corresponding, correlated states simultaneously.",
      "source": "target",
